					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">socram8888 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Instead of interfacing a 5V cartridge</div><br />So now you're looking to make a Kevtendo. But without interfacing a cartridge, you have no way of (lawfully) obtaining ROM images to run on an FPGA NES clone. Even for homebrew, you can't be sure that you're emulating (for example) the MMC5 correctly. Mapper compatibility might be comparable to that of the PowerPak: it took a few revisions to get MMC3 working perfectly. And good luck running cartridges with their own CPU and PPU, such as a Wide Boy or <a href="http://www.retrousb.com/product_info.php?cPath=&amp;products_id=87" class="postlink">RetroVision</a>.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">allow users to select which channel should go in each speaker in the game selection menu.</div>
<br />Setting a pan value for each channel at reset works for some games but not for others. For example, my sound engine automatically moves Square 1 sound effects to Square 2 under some circumstances so that two sound effects can play at once. Try playing LJ65 in VirtualNES and moving the pieces around rapidly to hear what can go wrong. For best results, games would have to be modified to write to the enhanced APU's pan register at runtime.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

